[2] Russia (Murmansk)
Date: Tue 31 Jan 2012
Source: Komsomolskaya Pravda [In Russian, trans. by CP. edited]
http://murmansk.kp.ru/online/news/1071779/

Measles arrives in Murmansk -- capital of the Arctic
----------------------------------------------------
As can be seen from the reports of the federal media, measles is raging in some regions of Russia. Measles is an acute infectious disease, the symptoms of which are difficult to distinguish from allergies and colds. The danger is that it can causes complications leading even to encephalitis . Measles outbreaks have occurred already in Podolsk, Novosibirsk and Tambov regions, and in Moscow. Typically, the infection has been imported. Likewise in Murmansk -- the capital of the Arctic. Th first case arrived from Ukraine on train number 22 St. Petersburg - Murmansk. A 23 year-old man arrived in Murmansk on 16 Jan 2012 and fell ill on the 17 Jan 2012 with the characteristic rash appearing on the 23rd. He is now in the Murmansk Infectious Diseases Hospital. A list has been compiled of 22 persons who were traveling with theyoung man on the train from St. Petersburg. Of them 21 are adults and one a child. They will be under surveillance up to 6 Feb 2012.

The 2nd case -- a 30 year-old man, arrived by private car on 27 Jan 2012 from the Tambov region, where he had contact with measles on 16 Jan 2012. He became ill on arrival and was hospitalised. Fortunately, he had no contact with anyone in Murmansk other than 2 physicians and an ambulance crew

Vaccination is the best protection against measles virus infection. If you have not been vaccinated in childhood, it is not too late to be vaccinated. Go to the nearest community health centre without delay, otherwise you are at risk of infection. At present, the disease remains widespread in the Southern Federal District, in the Volga region, in Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, as well as many parts of Euorope..

--
