[3] Russia (St Petersburg)
Date: Wed 1 Feb 2012
Source: INFOX.re [In Russian, trans. by CP, edited]
http://www.infox.ru/03/body/2012/01/31/V_Pyetyerburgye_____.phtml


Measles outbreak in St. Petersburg
----------------------------------
For the 1st time in several decades there has been an outbreak of measles in St Petersburg. According to the "Rosbalt" news agency, citing the press service of Rospotrebnadzor in St. Petersburg, 26 cases of meals in children and 5 in adults have been diagnosed in the city.

The measles index case came from a different region of Russia. The case was a 16-year-old girl who arrived back in the city after the winter break to continue her studies in one of the colleges of the city. Her infection was diagnosed on 13 Jan 2012, the day of her return and she was admitted to the St Petersburg Children's City Hospital № 1, and later transferred to the Filatov Children's Clinical Hospital.

The Rospotrebnadzor [health and welfare] organisation in St Petersburg is not underestimating the seriousness of the situation. Measles is an acute infectious viral disease transmitted by airborne droplets. It can be a dangerous disease with severe consequences, such as pneumonia, encephalitis or meningoencephalitis. Unvaccinated or incompletely vaccinated individuals are at risk if in contact with measles cases.

Vaccination is the only means of providing protection against measles virus infection. The national programme of vaccination requires vaccination of all children at 1 year of age, and revaccination at 6 years of age. Previously unvaccinated individersons in the age range 18-35 years. should also receive two vaccinations. Likewise health professionals and the staff of pre-school educational establijsments should be vaccinated against measles without any age restrictions.

