[5] New Zealand (Porirua)
Date: Thu 2 Feb 2012
Source: The Dominion Post [pedited]
http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/6354597/Porirua-measles-cases-prompt-alert


Porirua measles cases prompt alert
----------------------------------
Wellington health officials have issued an alert after seeing 3 cases of measles in Porirua already this year. Regional Public Health medical officer Margot McLean said general practitioners had been warned about measles in the area and asked to be extra vigilant to avoid a community spread.

All of the Porirua cases were thought to be related to South Auckland. The 1st case was a teenager who had come back from a holiday in South Auckland in early January, followed by a household member 2 weeks later. The last case was a child who had not had any obvious contact with the earlier cases, but who Dr McLean believed was probably related.

The cases follow on from a countrywide outbreak of measles last year that was mainly linked to travel to Auckland, she said. Wellington alone had 14 cases in 2011. Measles had a high rate of complications and more than 10 per cent of those contracting the disease ended up in hospital.

The latest 3 patients were now recovered, Dr McLean said. Parents are asked to ensure babies are vaccinated by 12 months' old, 3 months earlier than normal. The next vaccination should be at 4 years' old. Symptoms initially include fever, feeling unwell, coughs and runny noses, followed by a rash that crept from the head down.

--
